          "body": "The opening scene is the chapter's quietest but theologically densest. Elisha's warning (8:1) sends the Shunammite woman into a seven-year exile — not because of her sin but because of a divinely appointed famine. Her obedience to the prophetic word is total and immediate (8:2), exactly as the text records of her in chapter 4 (4:15-16). When she returns and appeals to the king for her property, the narrator inserts what appears to be coincidence but is in fact theological design: the very moment she walks into the throne room, Gehazi is recounting to the king the very miracle in which she and her son were involved (8:4-5). The word 'behold' (*hinneh*, 8:5) signals narrative surprise — the reader is meant to feel the shock of the coincidence and then recognize it as providence. There is no coincidence in Kings; there is only God arranging circumstances to fulfill His word. The king's response — full restitution plus seven years' produce (8:6) — is the most lavish outcome the chapter offers any character. Obedience to the prophetic word yields surplus. It is the chapter's pastoral opening note: those who act on God's word receive more than they lost."
