          "title": "The chapter's unity — one sovereign word over three scenes",
          "body": "What unites the Shunammite's restoration, Hazael's usurpation, and the Judean kings' corruption is not a common theme in the modern sense but a common agent: the word of the LORD spoken through His prophet. In scene one, Elisha's warning sends the woman into exile and his miracle is being recounted at the precise moment she needs it — the word orchestrates the timing. In scene two, the word Elisha received from the LORD (shown to him, 8:10, 13) determines who will die, who will live, and who will reign in Damascus — the word overrides human schemes. In scene three, the LORD's word to David (the lamp promise, 8:19) overrides Jehoram's wickedness and keeps the dynasty intact — the word restrains divine judgment. Throughout 2 Kings, the book has been making this case: Israel and Judah stand or fall not on the basis of military strength, royal wisdom, or political alliance, but on whether the word of the LORD is heard and obeyed. Chapter 8 demonstrates the same thesis in three registers — individual (the woman), international (Damascus), and dynastic (Judah). The word governs all three."
